And the tests you had all occured with 2+ drives.  They were interleaving the drives like I said earlier.  That means if someone goes out on one of the drives you lose it ALL!  They don't show a benefit of one drive running Raid0 because it would suck versus a normal drive.<br>
<br>
<br>
Ok on Ram,<br>
<br>
RD Ram or Rambus Ram was made for the Intel Platform Only.  It was fast and heated up and has a major heat sink on them.  The company Rambus held a strangle hold on the patent and charged up to $300 a stick.<br>
<br>
SD Ram is a conglomeration of companies that hated Rambus.  They created SD ram which as was fast and cheaper.  It became the defacto standard for all AMD machines as they had just released the new 1 Ghz chips.  These chips started at $100 (Back then, now they are like $30).  <br>
<br>
Intel started to lose the market, so they invent the I860 Chipset for motherboards.  I860 used SDRam, and then Intel could keep up with the market again.<br>
<br>
Rambus stock took a hit after SDRam was released and took another hit after the market crash.  And yet another hit when I860 came out.  So soon Rambus will be gone and RDRam with it.  <br>
<br>
So if you get rambus upgrades will be expensive IF they are available at all in the future.<br>
<br>
