<br>
What the article refers to as no fault tolerance is in comparison to other raid arrays, ie raid 0+1, raid 5.  Guess what... there's no fault tolerance with a single drive either!<br>
And raid 0 with a single drive? wtf are you smoking... you can't set up a raid array with only one drive, hence the term ARRAY<br>
<br>
As far as RDRAM, it still is the fastest ram around, doesn't really get that hot, and has a very small heatsink... hardly major.  Comparing PC800 RDRAM with 333 DDR they are pretty close, but PC1066 raised the bar again and is once again the fastest ram around.  It also is not going away, Intel still has RDRAM on it's roadmap for the future HIGH END system.  (btw, the 860 chipset is for xeon cpu's, the 850 is for P4 and RDRAM, and there are a few different versions of the 845 that support DDR / SDRAM)  Stay far away from SDRAM on a P4, it'll kill the performance <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/ubinadel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Binadel</A> at: 9/27/02 1:51:03 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/ucolossusa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Colossusa</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>S&M Barbie</span><br>  Posts: 75<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/27/02 1:58:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3753.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://colossusa.50megs.com/colo1.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Raid 0</span><hr size=1> Lol Binadel Raid 0 doesn't mean you have an array.  <br>
Here's something from the Tom's hardware page<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> RAID</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Number of drives</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Data security Availability Capacity Performance Cost <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 0 <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1+</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> unsatisfactory bad 100% very good very low <br>
1 2 good good 50% satisfactory low <br>
3 3+ satisfactory good (x-1) / x satisfactory medium <br>
5 3+ satisfactory good (x-1) / x good medium <br>
0+1 4,6,8... good good 50% good medium <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Raid 0 consists of keeping a check digit after comparing the bits of all the previous digits.  What that really means is that you lose 1/7th (Depending on the raid configuration) and that 7th is used to recover data in case of a bad sector occurs.  <br>
Raid 3 and Raid 5 do this better because they actually stripe the data across different drives.  Those are Raid Arrays, Raid 0 does not have to be in an array.  And it doesn't matter because Raid 0's are stored in a single drive, hence their post of no fault tolerance.  If the drive fails, the RAID fails.  <br>
<br>
Anyhow that is moot as Cuthulas is talking about Interleaving where you put information across more than one drive, using the caching and rpms of both drives to get a really good single drive.  That is not recommended as one failure will cause your whole array to go down. <br>
<br>
<br>
[Rambus]<br>
I never said PC800 was worse than SDRam,  I just said that Rambus is going <br>
away.  The problem with Rambus is the price.  The people at Rambus is RAPING the market at their prices and it took the invention of SDRam to wake them up.<br>
Look at their Stock Price, $110 on Jun 00 after a stock split of 4:1.  Around $7 around Aug 01 (Before 9/11) now at $4 today.  This is wallstreet.  Rambus is hurting for cash in a big way.<br>
